Hi Kailey,

Thank you for reaching out! We can gladly tell you how to swap your vehicles.

A Root policy always has to have at least one vehicle insured. When you are ready to change the vehicles on your policy, you will need to add the new vehicle to the policy first, then remove the old vehicle. 

Here are the steps:
1\. Go to Auto Policy, and then select Profile Information
2\. Select New Vehicle \- enter the 17\-digit VIN and hit Continue.
3\. Tap on the vehicle you want to remove from the policy.
4\. Remove the vehicle by tapping the trash can in the upper right\-hand corner.

Once you have deleted the vehicle\(s\), you will return to the profile screen. Continue forward to review coverages and see your new rate.

Changes are not saved until you complete the checkout process.

That said, you may be required to reinstate your policy as it was canceled on March 28, 2023 as requested. If your policy is canceled, there may be a lapse in coverage.

Hi Shronna,

Thank you so much for reaching out back to Root! My name is Salvador, and it will be my pleasure to assist you regarding your inquiry on Roadside Assistance.

Roadside Assistance is included with every policy \(unless you live in California, where it’s optional\).

You can request Roadside Assistance directly in the app. Here's how:
Open the app
Tap on Claims & Roadside
Tap on Roadside Assistance
Tap on Request Roadside Assistance
​

Eligible services up to $100 are covered for vehicles on your policy, up to three incidents per 6\-month policy term per vehicle. If you choose to use another Roadside Assistance provider, email all itemized receipts to roadside@joinroot.com for reimbursement.

Hi Titus Mayfield

Thanks for reaching out—great question. Please allow me to guide you on how you can edit this coverage on the app.

No car insurance coverage goes by the name “full coverage,”  but most folks think of full coverage as a policy that combines the following:
• State\-required liability or no\-fault insurance coverage to cover bodily injury and property damages to others in an accident you cause.
• Collision coverage to pay for damages to your vehicle in the event of an accident.
• Comprehensive coverage covers vandalism, theft, storm damage, and other damages that do not result from an accident.

For more info, check out our FAQ page \(joinroot.com/help/\), all coverage options \(joinroot.com/coverage/\), or one of our blogs like Car insurance in everyday English \(joinroot.com/blog/how\-to\-choose…\).

Hi Raul,

Thanks for reaching out. Sorry you’re having trouble processing your payment.

Here are some troubleshooting tips to try.
Try deleting all other cards on file and reentering the card you want to use.
Check that your card’s expiration date is correct.
Verify you have the funds in your account to make the payment.
Contact your bank to make sure the charge isn’t being flagged as fraud or that overdraft protection isn’t preventing the transaction.
Verify the address for the card matches the address for your Root account.

Hopefully, this helps you to successfully make your payment. Let us know if you still have problems or additional questions.

Hi Madeline,

Thanks for reaching out to inquire about your renewal rate change. We’re happy to explain.

Every six months, Root re\-evaluates many of the rate\-determining factors that we looked at initially to see if anything has changed over the course of the current policy term that would cause a greater risk during the next policy term.  If the risk has increased in any way, adjustments to your rate may be made so that we can continue to be able to effectively cover anything that might create a loss for you in the future. In order to reassess the risk, we review the 3 types of changes that could affect you as a driver and policyholder: changes on your end, changes around you, and changes on our end.

Changes on your end include various “controllable” factors such as potential changes to driving history such as tickets, claims filed, accidents, and so on.

Changes around you are the “uncontrollable” factors related to renewal rate and include things like:

If you decide to cancel your policy, you are responsible for doing so yourself.

You will have two options:

• Cancellation effective immediately

If you need to cancel on a specific day that is not the end of your policy term, you will need to make sure you cancel in the app on that specific day.

Hi Tisha,

Thank you so much for reaching out back to Root!

It will be our pleasure to assist you regarding your inquiries about the cancellation threshold.

When the system identifies the payment is overdue, it automatically generates a cancellation notice with a certain deadline on it. 

When this happens it means we, unfortunately, will not be able to help you modify it as it is an automated process. 

However, if a policy surpasses the threshold and gets canceled due to non\-payment, you could still be eligible for reinstatement.

In other words, if your policy is eligible for reinstatement, and you are the Primary Named Insured, then you’ll be able to determine if you’re eligible to reinstate in the app. The option to reinstate must be present, and if any incident that could give rise to a claim occurred during the time the policy was canceled, there could be a lapse of coverage due to the policy not being active.

Thanks for reaching out. You can add a lien holder \(loan/lease company\) to your policy directly in the app.

Here’s how:
Tap Auto Policy.
Select Vehicles, Loans, and Leases.
Select Add Loan/Lease Company
Enter the company’s name and Continue.
Enter the address and click the orange arrow.
Choose the vehicle with the lien or lease
Enter the routing number and/or the loan/account number \- Optional
Choose if the vehicle is leased and select Continue
​
​Once you’ve filled out and saved this information in the Root app, we’ll contact your lien holder for you. They’ll receive all of the information they need within one week.

Thanks for reaching out to inquire about your renewal rate change. I'm sorry the rate was not what you were expecting. It is my pleasure to explain your renewal rate. 

Every six months, Root re\-evaluates many of the rate\-determining factors that we looked at initially to see if anything has changed over the course of the current policy term that would cause a greater risk during the next policy term.  If the risk has increased in any way, adjustments to your rate may be made so that we can continue to be able to effectively cover anything that might create a loss for you in the future. In order to reassess the risk, we review the 3 types of changes that could affect you as a driver and policyholder: changes on your end, changes around you, and changes on our end.

Changes on your end include various “controllable” factors such as potential changes to driving history such as tickets, claims filed, accidents, and so on.
